** The Lonely City: Adventures in the Art of Being Alone (https://www.brai=
npickings.org/2016/07/11/the-lonely-city-olivia-laing/?mc_cid=3D584266f283=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1250039576/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D584266f=
283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CYou are born alone. You die alone. The value of the space in betw=
een is trust and love=2C=E2=80=9D artist Louise Bourgeoise wrote in her di=
ary at the end of a long and illustrious life as she contemplated how soli=
tude enriches creative work (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/15/loui=
se-bourgeois-solitude/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . It=E2=80=
=99s a lovely sentiment=2C but as empowering as it may be to those willing=
 to embrace solitude=2C it can be tremendously lonesome-making to those fo=
r whom loneliness has contracted the space of trust and love into a suffoc=
ating penitentiary. For if in solitude=2C as Wendell Berry memorably wrote=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/12/17/wendell-berry-pride-despair-sol=
itude/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C =E2=80=9Cone=E2=80=99s=
 inner voices become audible [and] one responds more clearly to other liv=
es=2C=E2=80=9D in loneliness one=E2=80=99s inner scream becomes deafening=
=2C deadening=2C severing any thread of connection to other lives.

How to break free of that prison and reinhabit the space of trust and love=
 is what Olivia Laing explores in The Lonely City: Adventures in the Art o=
f Being Alone (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1250039576/bpnl-20?m=
c_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldca=
t.org/title/lonely-city-adventures-in-the-art-of-being-alone/oclc/90568563=
9&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=
=94 an extraordinary more-than-memoir; a sort of memoir-plus-plus=2C partw=
ay between Helen MacDonald=E2=80=99s H Is for Hawk (https://www.brainpicki=
ngs.org/2015/12/16/h-is-for-hawk/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 and the diary of Virginia Woolf; a lyrical account of wading through a pe=
riod of self-expatriation=2C both physical and psychological=2C in which L=
aing paints an intimate portrait of loneliness as =E2=80=9Ca populated pla=
ce: a city in itself.=E2=80=9D

Art by Isol from Daytime Visions (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/25=
/daytime-visions-isol/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

After the sudden collapse of a romance marked by extreme elation=2C Laing=
 left her native England and took her shattered heart to New York=2C =E2=
=80=9Cthat teeming island of gneiss and concrete and glass.=E2=80=9D The d=
aily=2C bone-deep loneliness she experienced there was both paralyzing in=
 its all-consuming potency and=2C paradoxically=2C a strange invitation to=
 aliveness. Indeed=2C her choice to leave home and wander a foreign city i=
s itself a rich metaphor for the paradoxical nature of loneliness=2C anima=
ted by equal parts restlessness and stupor=2C capable of turning one into=
 a voluntary vagabond and a catatonic recluse all at once=2C yet somehow a=
 vitalizing laboratory for self-discovery. The pit of loneliness=2C she fo=
und=2C could =E2=80=9Cdrive one to consider some of the larger questions o=
f what it is to be alive.=E2=80=9D

She writes:

There were things that burned away at me=2C not only as a private individu=
al=2C but also as a citizen of our century=2C our pixelated age. What does=
 it mean to be lonely? How do we live=2C if we=E2=80=99re not intimately e=
ngaged with another human being? How do we connect with other people=2C pa=
rticularly if we don=E2=80=99t find speaking easy? Is sex a cure for lonel=
iness=2C and if it is=2C what happens if our body or sexuality is consider=
ed deviant or damaged=2C if we are ill or unblessed with beauty? And is te=
chnology helping with these things? Does it draw us closer together=2C or=
 trap us behind screens?

Bedeviled by this acute emotional anguish=2C Laing seeks consolation in th=
e great patron saints of loneliness in twentieth-century creative culture.=
 From this eclectic tribe of the lonesome =E2=80=94 including Jean-Michel=
 Basquiat=2C Alfred Hitchcock=2C Peter Hujar=2C Billie Holiday=2C and Nan=
 Goldin =E2=80=94 Laing chooses four artists as her companions charting th=
e terra incognita of loneliness: Edward Hopper=2C Andy Warhol=2C Henry Dar=
ger=2C and David Wojnarowicz=2C who had all =E2=80=9Cgrappled in their liv=
es as well as work with loneliness and its attendant issues.=E2=80=9D

Olivia Laing

She considers=2C for instance=2C Warhol =E2=80=94 an artist whom Laing had=
 always dismissed until the was submerged in loneliness herself. (=E2=80=
=9CI=E2=80=99d seen the screen-printed cows and Chairman Maos a thousand t=
imes=2C and I thought they were vacuous and empty=2C disregarding them as=
 we often do with things we=E2=80=99ve looked at but failed properly to se=
e.=E2=80=9D) She writes:

Warhol=E2=80=99s art patrols the space between people=2C conducting a gran=
d philosophical investigation into closeness and distance=2C intimacy and=
 estrangement. Like many lonely people=2C he was an inveterate hoarder=2C=
 making and surrounding himself with objects=2C barriers against the deman=
ds of human intimacy. Terrified of physical contact=2C he rarely left the=
 house without an armoury of cameras and tape recorders=2C using them to b=
roker and buffer interactions: behaviour that has light to shed on how we=
 deploy technology in our own century of so-called connectivity.

Woven into the fabric of Laing=E2=80=99s personal experience are inquiries=
 into the nature=2C context=2C and background of these four artists=E2=80=
=99 lives and their works most preoccupied with loneliness. But just as it=
 would be unfair to call Laing=E2=80=99s masterpiece only a =E2=80=9Cmemoi=
r=2C=E2=80=9D it would be unfair to call these threads =E2=80=9Cart histor=
y=2C=E2=80=9D for they are rather the opposite=2C a kind of =E2=80=9Cart p=
resent=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 elegant and erudite meditations on how art is pr=
esent with us=2C how it invites us to be present with ourselves and bears=
 witness to that presence=2C alleviating our loneliness in the process.

Laing examines the particular=2C pervasive form of loneliness in the eye o=
f a city aswirl with humanity:

Imagine standing by a window at night=2C on the sixth or seventeenth or fo=
rty-third floor of a building. The city reveals itself as a set of cells=
=2C a hundred thousand windows=2C some darkened and some flooded with gree=
n or white or golden light. Inside=2C strangers swim to and fro=2C attendi=
ng to the business of their private hours. You can see them=2C but you can=
=E2=80=99t reach them=2C and so this commonplace urban phenomenon=2C avail=
able in any city of the world on any night=2C conveys to even the most soc=
ial a tremor of loneliness=2C its uneasy combination of separation and exp=
osure.

You can be lonely anywhere=2C but there is a particular flavour to the lon=
eliness that comes from living in a city=2C surrounded by millions of peop=
le. One might think this state was antithetical to urban living=2C to the=
 massed presence of other human beings=2C and yet mere physical proximity=
 is not enough to dispel a sense of internal isolation. It=E2=80=99s possi=
ble =E2=80=93 easy=2C even =E2=80=93 to feel desolate and unfrequented in=
 oneself while living cheek by jowl with others. Cities can be lonely plac=
es=2C and in admitting this we see that loneliness doesn=E2=80=99t necessa=
rily require physical solitude=2C but rather an absence or paucity of conn=
ection=2C closeness=2C kinship: an inability=2C for one reason or another=
=2C to find as much intimacy as is desired. Unhappy=2C as the dictionary h=
as it=2C as a result of being without the companionship of others. Hardly=
 any wonder=2C then=2C that it can reach its apotheosis in a crowd.

As scientists are continuing to unpeel the physiological effects of loneli=
ness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/06/23/nothing-jo-marchant-heal-th=
yself/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C it is no surprise that=
 this psychological state comes with an almost bodily dimension=2C which L=
aing captures vividly:

What does it feel like to be lonely? It feels like being hungry: like bein=
g hungry when everyone around you is readying for a feast. It feels shamef=
ul and alarming=2C and over time these feelings radiate outwards=2C making=
 the lonely person increasingly isolated=2C increasingly estranged. It hur=
ts=2C in the way that feelings do=2C and it also has physical consequences=
 that take place invisibly=2C inside the closed compartments of the body.=
 It advances=2C is what I=E2=80=99m trying to say=2C cold as ice and clear=
 as glass=2C enclosing and engulfing.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1250039576/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D584266f=
283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

There is=2C of course=2C a universe of difference between solitude and lon=
eliness =E2=80=94 two radically different interior orientations toward the=
 same exterior circumstance of lacking companionship. We speak of =E2=80=
=9Cfertile solitude=E2=80=9D as a developmental achievement essential for=
 our creative capacity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/07/18/adam-phil=
lips-on-risk-and-solitude/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C but=
 loneliness is barren and destructive; it cottons in apathy the will to cr=
eate. More than that=2C it seems to signal an existential failing =E2=80=
=94 a social stigma the nuances of which Laing addresses beautifully:

Loneliness is difficult to confess; difficult too to categorise. Like depr=
ession=2C a state with which it often intersects=2C it can run deep in the=
 fabric of a person=2C as much a part of one=E2=80=99s being as laughing e=
asily or having red hair. Then again=2C it can be transient=2C lapping in=
 and out in reaction to external circumstance=2C like the loneliness that=
 follows on the heels of a bereavement=2C break-up or change in social cir=
cles.

Like depression=2C like melancholy or restlessness=2C it is subject too to=
 pathologisation=2C to being considered a disease. It has been said emphat=
ically that loneliness serves no purpose=E2=80=A6 Perhaps I=E2=80=99m wron=
g=2C but I don=E2=80=99t think any experience so much a part of our common=
 shared lives can be entirely devoid of meaning=2C without a richness and=
 a value of some kind.

With an eye to Virginia Woolf=E2=80=99s unforgettable diary writings on lo=
neliness and creativity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/16/virginia=
-woolf-loneliness/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Laing specu=
lates:

Loneliness might be taking you towards an otherwise unreachable experience=
 of reality.

Adrift and alone in the city that promises its inhabitants =E2=80=9Cthe gi=
ft of privacy with the excitement of participation=2C=E2=80=9D (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2014/07/09/e-b-white-here-is-new-york/?mc_cid=3D584266=
f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Laing cycles through a zoetrope of temporary home=
s =E2=80=94 sublets=2C friends=E2=80=99 apartments=2C and various borrowed=
 quarters=2C only amplifying the sense of otherness and alienation as she=
 is forced to make =E2=80=9Ca life among someone else=E2=80=99s things=2C=
 in a home that someone else has created and long since.=E2=80=9D

Art by Carson Ellis from Home (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/09/ca=
rson-ellis-home/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

But therein lies an inescapable metaphor for life itself =E2=80=94 we are=
=2C after all=2C subletting our very existence from a city and a society a=
nd a world that have been there for much longer than we have=2C already ar=
ranged in a way that might not be to our taste=2C that might not be how th=
e building would be laid out and its interior designed were we to do it fr=
om scratch ourselves. And yet we are left to make ourselves at home in the=
 way things are=2C imperfect and sometimes downright ugly. The measure of=
 a life has to do with this subletting ability =E2=80=94 with how well we=
 are able to settle into this borrowed=2C imperfect abode and how much bea=
uty we can bring into existence with however little control over its desig=
n we may have.

This=2C perhaps=2C is why Laing found her only=2C if temporary=2C respite=
 from loneliness in an activity propelled by the very act of leaving this=
 borrowed home: walking. In a passage that calls to mind Robert Walser=E2=
=80=99s exquisite serenade to the soul-nourishment of the walk (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2015/02/11/the-walk-robert-walser/?mc_cid=3D584266f283=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C she writes:

In certain circumstances=2C being outside=2C not fitting in=2C can be a so=
urce of satisfaction=2C even pleasure. There are kinds of solitude that pr=
ovide a respite from loneliness=2C a holiday if not a cure. Sometimes as I=
 walked=2C roaming under the stanchions of the Williamsburg Bridge or foll=
owing the East River all the way to the silvery hulk of the U.N.=2C I coul=
d forget my sorry self=2C becoming instead as porous and borderless as the=
 mist=2C pleasurably adrift on the currents of the city.

But whatever semblance of a more solid inner center these peripatetic esca=
pes into solitude offered=2C it was a brittle solidity:

I didn=E2=80=99t get this feeling when I was in my apartment; only when I=
 was outside=2C either entirely alone or submerged in a crowd. In these si=
tuations I felt liberated from the persistent weight of loneliness=2C the=
 sensation of wrongness=2C the agitation around stigma and judgement and v=
isibility. But it didn=E2=80=99t take much to shatter the illusion of self=
-forgetfulness=2C to bring me back not only to myself but to the familiar=
=2C excruciating sense of lack.

Edward Hopper: Nighthawks (1942)

It was in the lacuna between self-forgetfulness and self-discovery that La=
ing found herself drawn to the artists who became her companions in a jour=
ney both toward and away from loneliness. There is Edward Hopper with his=
 iconic Nighthawks aglow in eerie jade=2C of which Laing writes:

There is no colour in existence that so powerfully communicates urban alie=
nation=2C the atomisation of human beings inside the edifices they create=
=2C as this noxious pallid green=2C which only came into being with the ad=
vent of electricity=2C and which is inextricably associated with the noctu=
rnal city=2C the city of glass towers=2C of empty illuminated offices and=
 neon signs.

[=E2=80=A6]

The diner was a place of refuge=2C absolutely=2C but there was no visible=
 entrance=2C no way to get in or out. There was a cartoonish=2C ochre-colo=
ured door at the back of the painting=2C leading perhaps into a grimy kitc=
hen. But from the street=2C the room was sealed: an urban aquarium=2C a gl=
ass cell.

[=E2=80=A6]

Green on green=2C glass on glass=2C a mood that expanded the longer I ling=
ered=2C breeding disquiet.

Hopper himself had a conflicted relationship with the common interpretatio=
n that loneliness was a central theme of his work. Although he often denie=
d that it was a deliberate creative choice=2C he once conceded in an inter=
view: =E2=80=9CI probably am a lonely one.=E2=80=9D Laing=2C whose attenti=
on and sensitivity to even the subtlest texture of experience are what mak=
e the book so wonderful=2C considers how Hopper=E2=80=99s choice of langua=
ge captures the essence of loneliness:

It=E2=80=99s an unusual formulation=2C a lonely one; not at all the same t=
hing as admitting one is lonely. Instead=2C it suggests with that a=2C tha=
t unassuming indefinite article=2C a fact that loneliness by its nature re=
sists. Though it feels entirely isolating=2C a private burden no one else=
 could possibly experience or share=2C it is in reality a communal state=
=2C inhabited by many people. In fact=2C current studies suggest that more=
 than a quarter of American adults suffers from loneliness=2C independent=
 of race=2C education and ethnicity=2C while 45 per cent of British adults=
 report feeling lonely either often or sometimes. Marriage and high income=
 serve as mild deterrents=2C but the truth is that few of us are absolutel=
y immune to feeling a greater longing for connection than we find ourselve=
s able to satisfy. The lonely ones=2C a hundred million strong. Hardly any=
 wonder Hopper=E2=80=99s paintings remain so popular=2C and so endlessly r=
eproduced.

Reading his halting confession=2C one begins to see why his work is not ju=
st compelling but also consoling=2C especially when viewed en masse. It=E2=
=80=99s true that he painted=2C not once but many times=2C the loneliness=
 of a large city=2C where the possibilities of connection are repeatedly d=
efeated by the dehumanising apparatus of urban life. But didn=E2=80=99t he=
 also paint loneliness as a large city=2C revealing it as a shared=2C demo=
cratic place=2C inhabited=2C whether willingly or not=2C by many souls?

[=E2=80=A6]

What Hopper captures is beautiful as well as frightening. They aren=E2=80=
=99t sentimental=2C his pictures=2C but there is an extraordinary attentiv=
eness to them=E2=80=A6 As if loneliness was something worth looking at. Mo=
re than that=2C as if looking itself was an antidote=2C a way to defeat lo=
neliness=E2=80=99s strange=2C estranging spell.

David Wojnarowicz by Peter Hujar (Peter Hujar Archive)

For the artists accompanying Laing on her journey =E2=80=94 including Henr=
y Darger=2C the brilliant and mentally ill Chicago janitor whose posthumou=
sly discovered paintings made him one of the most celebrated outsider arti=
sts of the twentieth century=2C and the creative polymath David Wojnarowic=
z=2C still in his thirties when AIDS took his life =E2=80=94 loneliness wa=
s often twined with another profound affliction of the psyche: loss. In a=
 passage evocative of Paul Goodman=E2=80=99s taxonomy of the nine types of=
 silence (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/01/13/paul-goodman-silence/?m=
c_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Laing offers a taxonomy of lone=
linesses through the lens of loss:

Loss is a cousin of loneliness. They intersect and overlap=2C and so it=E2=
=80=99s not surprising that a work of mourning might invoke a feeling of a=
loneness=2C of separation. Mortality is lonely. Physical existence is lone=
ly by its nature=2C stuck in a body that=E2=80=99s moving inexorably towar=
ds decay=2C shrinking=2C wastage and fracture. Then there=E2=80=99s the lo=
neliness of bereavement=2C the loneliness of lost or damaged love=2C of mi=
ssing one or many specific people=2C the loneliness of mourning.

But this lonesomeness of mortality finds its antidote in the abiding conso=
lations of immortal works of art. =E2=80=9CArt holds out the promise of in=
ner wholeness=2C=E2=80=9D philosopher Alain de Botton and art historian Jo=
hn Armstrong wrote in their inquiry into the seven psychological functions=
 of art (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/10/25/art-as-therapy-alain-de-=
botton-john-armstrong/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and if=
 loneliness is=2C as Laing puts it=2C =E2=80=9Ca longing for integration=
=2C for a sense of feeling whole=2C=E2=80=9D what better answer to that lo=
nging than art? After all=2C in the immortal words of James Baldwin (https=
://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/13/james-baldwin-the-artists-struggle-for=
-integrity/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C =E2=80=9Conly an a=
rtist can tell=2C and only artists have told since we have heard of man=2C=
 what it is like for anyone who gets to this planet to survive it.=E2=80=
=9D

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1250039576/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D584266f=
283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Looking back on her experience=2C Laing writes:

There are so many things that art can=E2=80=99t do. It can=E2=80=99t bring=
 the dead back to life=2C it can=E2=80=99t mend arguments between friends=
=2C or cure AIDS=2C or halt the pace of climate change. All the same=2C it=
 does have some extraordinary functions=2C some odd negotiating ability be=
tween people=2C including people who never meet and yet who infiltrate and=
 enrich each other=E2=80=99s lives. It does have a capacity to create inti=
macy; it does have a way of healing wounds=2C and better yet of making it=
 apparent that not all wounds need healing and not all scars are ugly.

If I sound adamant it is because I am speaking from personal experience. W=
hen I came to New York I was in pieces=2C and though it sounds perverse=2C=
 the way I recovered a sense of wholeness was not by meeting someone or by=
 falling in love=2C but rather by handling the things that other people ha=
d made=2C slowly absorbing by way of this contact the fact that loneliness=
=2C longing=2C does not mean one has failed=2C but simply that one is aliv=
e.

But as profoundly personal as loneliness may feel=2C it is inseparable fro=
m the political dimensions of public life. In a closing passage that calls=
 to mind Audre Lorde=E2=80=99s clarion call for breaking our silences agai=
nst structural injustice (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/20/audre-l=
orde-silence-visibility/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Laing=
 adds:

There is a gentrification that is happening to cities=2C and there is a ge=
ntrification that is happening to the emotions too=2C with a similarly hom=
ogenising=2C whitening=2C deadening effect. Amidst the glossiness of late=
 capitalism=2C we are fed the notion that all difficult feelings =E2=80=94=
 depression=2C anxiety=2C loneliness=2C rage =E2=80=94 are simply a conseq=
uence of unsettled chemistry=2C a problem to be fixed=2C rather than a res=
ponse to structural injustice or=2C on the other hand=2C to the native tex=
ture of embodiment=2C of doing time=2C as David Wojnarowicz memorably put=
 it=2C in a rented body=2C with all the attendant grief and frustration th=
at entails.

I don=E2=80=99t believe the cure for loneliness is meeting someone=2C not=
 necessarily. I think it=E2=80=99s about two things: learning how to befri=
end yourself and understanding that many of the things that seem to afflic=
t us as individuals are in fact a result of larger forces of stigma and ex=
clusion=2C which can and should be resisted.

Loneliness is personal=2C and it is also political. Loneliness is collecti=
ve; it is a city. As to how to inhabit it=2C there are no rules and nor is=
 there any need to feel shame=2C only to remember that the pursuit of indi=
vidual happiness does not trump or excuse our obligations to each another.=
 We are in this together=2C this accumulation of scars=2C this world of ob=
jects=2C this physical and temporary heaven that so often takes on the cou=
ntenance of hell. What matters is kindness; what matters is solidarity. Wh=
at matters is staying alert=2C staying open=2C because if we know anything=
 from what has gone before us=2C it is that the time for feeling will not=
 last.

The Lonely City (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1250039576/bpnl-20=
?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) is a layered and endlessly reward=
ing book=2C among the finest I have ever read. Complement it with Rebecca=
 Solnit on how we find ourselves by getting lost (https://www.brainpicking=
s.org/2014/08/04/field-guide-to-getting-lost-rebecca-solnit/?mc_cid=3D5842=
66f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C David Whyte on the transfiguration of alone=
ness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/08/david-whyte-consolations-lo=
nging-silence/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Alfred Kazin on=
 loneliness and the immigrant experience (https://www.brainpickings.org/20=
16/07/05/alfred-kazin-walker-in-the-city-love/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and Sara Maitland on how to be alone without being lonel=
y (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/09/03/how-to-be-alone-school-of-life=
