** You Got Me Singing: Jack and Amanda Palmer=E2=80=99s Elegy for Time and=
 Ode to the Dignity of the Downtrodden and the Dispossessed (https://www.b=
rainpickings.org/2016/07/15/jack-and-amanda-palmer-you-got-me-singing/?mc_=
cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://shop.amandapalmer.net/=E2=80=9CAfter silence that which comes neare=
st to expressing the inexpressible is music=2C=E2=80=9D Aldous Huxley wrot=
e (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/05/aldous-huxley-music-at-night/?=
mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . It was near-silence that had str=
etched between Amanda Palmer (http://amandapalmer.net/?mc_cid=3D584266f283=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and her father=2C Jack=2C from the time she was nine=
 months old=2C when her mother left Jack=2C until she was an adult. And th=
en there was music =E2=80=94 music as memoir=2C music as lamentation=2C mu=
sic as the myriad inexpressible complexities that lie between regret and r=
edemption.

Jack and Amanda=2C 1977

In 2015=2C after nearly a decade of tentatively dancing around the idea of=
 collaborating=2C Jack and Amanda walked into the legendary Dreamland Stud=
io in upstate New York=2C founded by Albert Grossman=2C onetime manager of=
 Bob Dylan and Janis Joplin. The iconic cover of Dylan=E2=80=99s 1965 albu=
m Bringing It All Back Home was shot at Grossman=E2=80=99s house nearby.

The result =E2=80=94 a labor of love (http://amandapalmer.net/you-got-me-s=
inging/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) in every possible dimensio=
n of the phrase =E2=80=94 is the almost unbearably beautiful Jack and Aman=
da Palmer: You Got Me Singing (http://shop.amandapalmer.net/?mc_cid=3D5842=
66f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Gracing it is a cover staged after the Dylan=
 classic and photographed at the same location by Kyle Cassidy (http://www=
=2Ekylecassidy.com/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

I wrote the liner notes=2C which say everything I have to say about this m=
iraculously wonderful record (http://amandapalmer.bandcamp.com/album/you-g=
ot-me-singing-2?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) :

=E2=80=9CA society must assume that it is stable=2C=E2=80=9D James Baldwin=
 wrote (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/08/20/james-baldwin-the-creativ=
e-process/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C =E2=80=9Cbut the ar=
tist must know=2C and he must let us know=2C that there is nothing stable=
 under heaven.=E2=80=9D

Folk music=2C more than any other art=2C invites each generation to come t=
o terms with this perennial instability. Beneath the intergenerational dia=
logue between Jack and Amanda Palmer is a larger conversation with time th=
rough the inescapably entwined dimensions of the personal and the politica=
l. The twelve songs they spent years choosing together are a reminder that=
 what we experience as the present moment=2C with all of its shrieking urg=
ency=2C is a bellowing echo of a past yet to be redeemed. The trials and t=
riumphs of our time=2C from civil rights to marriage equality=2C have a ge=
stational period stretching back generations.

An album of cover songs=2C like culture itself=2C is an hourglass =E2=80=
=94 the same material passes through the narrow opening of the present=2C=
 back and forth=2C over and over again. Jack tweaked and retrofitted the l=
yrics to Phil Ochs=E2=80=99s piercing protest song =E2=80=9CIn the Heat of=
 the Summer=2C=E2=80=9D adding=2C =E2=80=9CAnother black kid facedown in t=
he road / whose life did not seem to matter=2C=E2=80=9D and suddenly the h=
alf-century between the Harlem riots of 1964 and the Black Lives Matter mo=
vement crumbles into a single grain of sand. Sin=C3=A9ad O=E2=80=99Connor=
 wrote =E2=80=9CBlack Boys On Mopeds=E2=80=9D in 1983=2C after a young bla=
ck man named Colin Roach was shot dead by British police and his killers w=
ere acquitted. As the song is beckoned back to life in the wake of Trayvon=
 Martin and Eric Garner=E2=80=99s deaths=2C we are chilled out of our self=
-congratulatory illusion of progress =E2=80=94 however far we may have com=
e=2C we have a long way to go.

There is a Victorian nursery rhyme=2C =E2=80=9CWynken=2C Blynken and Nod=
=2C=E2=80=9D a phantasmagorical children=E2=80=99s poem by Eugene Field wh=
ich was originally set to music by another family duo=2C Lucy and Carly Si=
moan. There is country death song (=E2=80=9CLouise=E2=80=9D)=2C a traditio=
nal Scottish lullaby (=E2=80=9CSkye Boat Song=E2=80=9D) about a journey to=
 Amanda=E2=80=99s immigrant Grandmother=E2=80=99s Island of Origin=2C a mo=
dern-day gay rights anthem (=E2=80=9CGlacier=E2=80=9D)=2C and an ode to si=
mple and humble human connection (=E2=80=9CI Love You So Much=E2=80=9D) wr=
itten by a hometown friend of Amanda=E2=80=99s. The songs are strung toget=
her by a connective thread woven of the old ideals of folk music =E2=80=94=
 ideals about equality and love and human dignity=2C all the more urgent t=
oday if there is any hope to be had for our civil society and our inner li=
ves.

When Amanda was nine months old=2C her parents=E2=80=99 separation brought=
 her up to Boston and left Jack in New York City. There were short visits=
 and school vacations and a somewhat reserved relationship; it wasn=E2=80=
=99t until Amanda was in her late twenties and touring solo=2C on her own=
 terms=2C that music created a new connective tissue between father and da=
ughter. They reentered each other=E2=80=99s lives through the gateway of c=
over songs; together=2C they played a Leonard Cohen tune (=E2=80=9CNight C=
omes On=E2=80=9D) at one of Amanda=E2=80=99s DC shows=2C and a year later=
=2C another one (=E2=80=9COne of Us Cannot Be Wrong=E2=80=9D). So began=
 =E2=80=94 in 2009 =E2=80=94 the tentative idea to record the songs for po=
sterity. Finally=2C in 2015=2C Jack and Amanda walked into Dreamland Studi=
o in rural upstate New York=2C recording for seven days straight. Those tw=
o Cohen songs didn=E2=80=99t make the list=2C but Jack suggested =E2=80=9C=
You Got Me Singing=E2=80=9D as a perfect statement to open the album.

=E2=80=9CAll of us=2C we=E2=80=99re links in a chain=2C=E2=80=9D Pete Seeg=
er=2C that great patron saint of protest music once observed (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2014/05/13/pete-seeger-paul-zollo-songwriters-on-songwri=
ting/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and there was another li=
nk on the way=E2=80=93 Amanda was seven months pregnant with her first chi=
ld. These timeless and acutely timely songs became a soundtrack to Anthony=
-and-Ash-for-short=E2=80=99s final weeks in his mother=E2=80=99s womb.

What emerges is a record of searing tenderness and sorrowful optimism=2C h=
armonizing heartbreak and hope =E2=80=94 for this particular father and da=
ughter=2C and for the world itself. This collection of songs is an elegy i=
n the proper sense =E2=80=94 a dialogue between loss and celebration=2C re=
minding us what we so easily forget: that every life carries weight; that=
 even the downtrodden and the dispossessed are animated by tremendous dign=
ity; that life is not something that happens to us=2C much less something=
 that has already happened to us=2C but something we actively construct an=
d calibrate each day.

The album=2C designed by Debbie Millman (http://debbiemillman.com?mc_cid=
=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and Emily Weiland (http://cargocollectiv=
e.com/emilyweiland/About?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C is av=
ailable in signed 180-gram vinyl (http://shop.amandapalmer.net/collections=
/featured/products/jack-amanda-palmer-you-got-me-singing-vinyl-pre-order?m=
c_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C signed or unsigned CD (http://s=
hop.amandapalmer.net/collections/featured/products/jack-amanda-palmer-you-=
got-me-singing-cd-pre-order?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C an=
d $1 digital download (http://shop.amandapalmer.net/collections/featured/p=
roducts/jack-amanda-palmer-you-got-me-singing-digital-download?mc_cid=3D58=
4266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

For a taste of the magic=2C here is a beautiful animated short film for on=
e of the songs on the record=2C Richard Thompson=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C1952 V=
incent Black Lightning=E2=80=9D=2C with art by David Mack (https://www.fac=
ebook.com/David-Mack-21231086294/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 :

https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/15/jack-and-amanda-palmer-you-got-me=
-singing/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

