** William Blake=E2=80=99s Most Beautiful Letter: The 20-Year-Old Artist=
=E2=80=99s Searing Defense of the Imagination and the Creative Spirit (htt=
ps://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/14/william-blake-john-trusler-letter/?m=
c_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0140150269/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D584266f=
283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CThe genius=2C=E2=80=9D Schopenhauer wrote in his timeless distinc=
tion between genius and talent (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/29/s=
chopenhauer-genius/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C =E2=80=9Cl=
ights on his age like a comet into the paths of the planets=2C to whose we=
ll-regulated and comprehensible arrangement its wholly eccentric course is=
 foreign.=E2=80=9D Unlike the person of talent=2C whose work simply exceed=
s in excellence the work of their contemporaries and is therefore easily a=
ppreciated by them=2C Schopenhauer argued that person of genius produces w=
ork which differs not in mere degree of excellence but in kind of vision.=
 It is therefore often ridiculed or=2C worse yet=2C entirely ignored by th=
e creator=E2=80=99s contemporaries=2C to be rediscovered and appreciated o=
nly by posterity.

Arguably no genius embodies this tragic tenet more perfectly than William=
 Blake (November 28=2C 1757=E2=80=93August 12=2C 1827)=2C who lived amid r=
idicule and died in relative obscurity=2C then went on to inspire generati=
ons of artists. He was a lifelong muse to Maurice Sendak (https://www.brai=
npickings.org/2014/06/10/maurice-sendak-william-blake-songs-of-innocence-1=
967/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and a kind of creative patron=
 saint for Patti Smith (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/19/patti-smi=
th-m-train-loss-time/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . He produce=
d stunning art for Milton=E2=80=99s Paradise Lost (https://www.brainpickin=
gs.org/2014/02/13/william-blake-paradise-lost/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) and labored over his drawings for Dante=E2=80=99s Divine Com=
edy (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/01/17/william-blake-dante-divine-c=
omedy/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) until his dying day. Centur=
ies later=2C his verses (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/04/22/beastly-=
verse-joohee-yoon/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) continue to que=
nch an immutable existential thirst.

Art by William Blake for a rare 1808 edition (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2014/02/13/william-blake-paradise-lost/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[U=
NIQID]) of Milton=E2=80=99s Paradise Lost

Blake=E2=80=99s genius sprang from his unusual spiritual disposition. Both=
 drawn to and discomfited by religion=2C he chose instead to live in a wor=
ld of abstract spirituality=2C amid a self-created cosmogony=2C agnostic a=
nd often unabashedly antagonistic to scripture. His was an irreverent reve=
rence=2C intellectually daring and contemptuous of dogma yet animated by u=
nflinching faith in the human spirit=2C in our capacity for self-transcend=
ence=2C and in the ability to ameliorate the sorrowful finitude of our liv=
es by contacting eternity through the supreme conduits of truth and beauty=
 =E2=80=94 truth and beauty that continue to radiate from his art. He may=
 have died in poverty=2C but he lived enriched and electrified by the mirt=
h of creativity.

Nowhere does Blake=E2=80=99s singular genius and orientation of spirit shi=
ne more brilliantly than in a letter he wrote to a Reverend John Trusler i=
n the summer of 1777=2C included in The Portable William Blake (http://www=
=2Eamazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0140150269/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/portable-blak=
e/oclc/3332209&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) )=2C edited by the great Alfred Kazin (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2016/07/05/alfred-kazin-walker-in-the-city-love/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_ei=
d=3D[UNIQID]) .

William Blake=2C =E2=80=9CThe Last Supper=E2=80=9D

Trusler was a priest and an early self-help entrepreneur of sorts=2C who a=
uthored books with titles like Hogarth Moralized=2C A Sure Way to Lengthen=
 Life with Vigor=2C and The Way to be Rich and Respectable. Practicing his=
 own preachings=2C he made non-negligible sums from his clever idea to sel=
l sermons printed to appear handwritten so as to relieve the corner-cuttin=
g devout of the drudgery of composition. After seeing Blake=E2=80=99s =E2=
=80=9CThe Last Supper=E2=80=9D exhibited at the Royal Academy in May of 17=
77=2C Trusler decided to commission him for a series of moralistically the=
med artworks intended to illustrate Trusler=E2=80=99s writings on subjects=
 such as malevolence=2C benevolence=2C pride=2C and humility.

But=2C as might be expected when a visionary is mistaken for a hand for hi=
re=2C trouble arose =E2=80=94 Blake had his own visions for the art=2C but=
 Trusler had very specific=2C rather crude ideas informed by the era=E2=80=
=99s popular caricature aesthetic () . He wrote to Blake with a litany of=
 criticisms=2C condemning his approach as overly transcendent and whimsica=
l=2C and accusing him of having an imagination that belongs to =E2=80=9Cth=
e world of spirits=E2=80=9D and unbefitting Trusler=E2=80=99s worldly inte=
ntions.

First and last pages of Blake=E2=80=99s letter to Trusler=2C August 23=2C=
 1777. (Images: British Library (http://www.bl.uk/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) )

On August 16=2C 1777=2C a clearly aggravated and artistically indignant tw=
enty-year-old Blake fires back in a letter brimming with the curious coali=
tion undergirding all of his art =E2=80=94 vexation with the status quo=2C=
 deep personal torment=2C and unassailable creative buoyancy. He writes to=
 Trusler:

I find more & more that my style of designing is a species by itself=2C an=
d in this which I send you have been compelled by my Genius or Angel to fo=
llow where he led; if I were to act otherwise it would not fulfill the pur=
pose for which alone I live=2C which is =E2=80=A6 to renew the lost art of=
 the Greeks.

I attempted every morning for a fortnight together to follow your dictate=
=2C but when I found my attempts were in vain=2C resolved to show an indep=
endence which I know will please an author better than slavishly following=
 the track of another=2C however admirable that track may be. At any rate=
=2C my excuse must be: I could not do otherwise; it was out of my power!

I know I begged of you to give me your ideas and promised to build on them=
; here I counted without my host. I now find my mistake.

In a sentiment that Tchaikovsky would echo exactly a century later in his=
 lamentation about the paradox of commissioned work and creative freedom (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/08/24/tchaikovsky-on-the-paradox-of-pat=
ronage/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Blake argues that what=
 prohibited him from obeying Trusler=E2=80=99s demands was the impossibili=
ty =E2=80=94 nay=2C the sacrilege =E2=80=94 of disobeying the muse:

[I] cannot previously describe in words what I mean to design=2C for fear=
 I should evaporate the spirit of my invention=E2=80=A6 And tho=E2=80=99 I=
 call them mine=2C I know that they are not mine=2C being of the same opin=
ion with Milton when he says that the Muse visits his slumbers and awakes=
 and governs his song when morn purples the East=2C and being also in the=
 predicament of that prophet who says: =E2=80=9CI cannot go beyond the com=
mand of the Lord=2C to speak good or bad.=E2=80=9D

One of Blake=E2=80=99s drawings for Dante=E2=80=99s Divine Comedy (https:/=
/www.brainpickings.org/2014/01/17/william-blake-dante-divine-comedy/?mc_ci=
d=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Trusler was incensed and fired further criticism. Before replying to Trusl=
er=2C Blake wryly confided in his dear friend and lifelong supporter Georg=
e Cumberland=2C who had introduced Trusler to Blake=E2=80=99s work and had=
 facilitated the commission: =E2=80=9CI could not help smiling at the diff=
erence between the doctrines of Dr. Trusler and those of Christ=2C=E2=80=
=9D

In what remains his greatest letter=2C Blake defends his vision to Trusler=
 =E2=80=94 but his words radiate a larger=2C more universal and eternal de=
fense of the creative spirit against all the forces which continually try=
 to corrupt it=2C contract it=2C and contain it within a suffocating small=
ness of purpose.

On August 23=2C 1777=2C a part-sincere=2C part-sardonic Blake addresses Tr=
usler=E2=80=99s complaint that his art warrants explanation and is simply=
 too imaginative:

I really am sorry that you are fallen out with the spiritual world=2C espe=
cially if I should have to answer for it=E2=80=A6 If I am wrong=2C I am wr=
ong in good company=E2=80=A6 What is grand is necessarily obscure to weak=
 men. That which can be made explicit to the idiot is not worth my care.

Asserting that Trusler=E2=80=99s eye has been =E2=80=9Cperverted by carica=
ture prints=2C which ought not to abound so much as they do=2C=E2=80=9D Bl=
ake makes a beautiful case for beauty (or ugliness) being in the eye of th=
e beholder=2C implying that the art of living lies largely in training the=
 eye to attend to what is beautiful and noble =E2=80=94 an argument all th=
e more urgent amid our present culture of rampant cynicism (https://www.br=
ainpickings.org/2016/05/16/annenberg-commencement/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) and a media ecosystem that traffics in outrage as its chi=
ef currency.

Blake writes:

Fun I love=2C but too much fun is of all things the most loathsome. Mirth=
 is better than fun=2C and happiness is better than mirth. I feel that a m=
an may be happy in this world. And I know that this world is a world of im=
agination and vision. I see every thing I paint in this world=2C but every=
body does not see alike. To the eyes of a miser a guinea is far more beaut=
iful than the Sun=2C and a bag worn with the use of money has more beautif=
ul proportions than a vine filled with grapes. The tree which moves some t=
o tears of joy is in the eyes of others only a green thing which stands in=
 the way. Some see nature all ridicule and deformity=2C and by these I sha=
ll not regulate my proportions; and some scarce see nature at all. But to=
 the eyes of the man of imagination=2C nature is imagination itself. As a=
 man is=2C so he sees.

[=E2=80=A6]

You certainly mistake=2C when you say that the visions of fancy are not to=
 be found in this world. To me this world is all one continued vision of f=
ancy or imagination=2C and I feel flattered when I am told so.

There is no greater testament to the enchantment of the real world=2C Blak=
e argues=2C than the imagination of children=2C who see the grand and eter=
nal in the ordinary and who are=2C as E.B. White would argue three centuri=
es later=2C =E2=80=9Cthe most attentive=2C curious=2C eager=2C observant=
=2C sensitive=2C quick=2C and generally congenial readers on earth.=E2=80=
=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/02/26/e-b-white-writing-for-childr=
en/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Blake writes:

I am happy to find a great majority of fellow mortals who can elucidate my=
 visions=2C and particularly they have been elucidated by children=2C who=
 have taken a greater delight in contemplating my pictures than I even hop=
ed. Neither youth nor childhood is folly or incapacity. Some children are=
 fools and so are some old men. But there is a vast majority on the side o=
f imagination or spiritual sensation.

Another of Blake=E2=80=99s drawings for Dante=E2=80=99s Divine Comedy (htt=
ps://www.brainpickings.org/2014/01/17/william-blake-dante-divine-comedy/?m=
c_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Complying with the era=E2=80=99s epistolary etiquette (https://www.brainpi=
ckings.org/2012/12/21/how-to-write-letters-1876/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_ei=
d=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Blake ends with a signature comically courteous in the=
 contrasting context of his defiant letter:

I am=2C Revd. Sir=2C your very obedient servant=2C

WILLIAM BLAKE.

Couple the altogether indispensable Portable William Blake (http://www.ama=
zon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0140150269/bpnl-20?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/portable-blake/oc=
lc/3332209&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 ) with Patti Smith=E2=80=99s loving homage to Blake (https://www.brainpic=
kings.org/2015/10/19/patti-smith-m-train-loss-time/?mc_cid=3D584266f283&mc=
_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then complement this particular portion with artist=
 Anne Truitt=E2=80=99s beautiful meditation on what sustains the creative=
 spirit (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/01/21/anne-truitt-turn-art/?mc=
_cid=3D584266f283&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


